# Task boundaries and new chats

There's no tool to clear context or start a new chat yourself, that's the user's action. Instead of staying silent, notice the boundary yourself and raise it as an explicit choice via AskUserQuestion, without waiting to be asked.

What a hook now enforces mechanically. Context size, a number from the transcript, is checked by the `context-check.sh` Stop hook (registered via the plugin's `hooks/hooks.json` on a plugin install, or an entry you add to `~/.claude/settings.json` yourself on a manual install, see INSTALL.md). It reads the summed usage of the last main-session assistant message (input + cache_creation + cache_read + output, subagent/sidechain entries excluded), tracks it per model so a `/model` switch does not corrupt the count, and on crossing a threshold blocks the response from ending (`decision:block`, exit 2). Thresholds derive from the model's window (default 200K, the standard account tier; override with `CONTEXT_CHECK_WINDOW=1000000` if your account runs the 1M-context tier, since the transcript carries no window-size hint to detect this automatically). The percentages below are shipped defaults too, every number here, plus turning either tier off outright, is configurable via `~/.claude/hooks/context-check.conf`, see CUSTOMIZE.md in the repo:

- Soft mark, 55% of the window (110k at the 200K default, 550k at 1M). An advisory nudge, enforced as text, not a forced tool call. In one line you either raise the checkpoint with AskUserQuestion, or, if this is focused continuous work that needs the accumulated history (the documented exception), say so and continue. The exception is yours to invoke here.
- Hard mark, 88% of the window (176k at the 200K default, 880k at 1M; before the harness force-compacts, empirically near ~99% of the window but observed as early as ~93% in some sessions, which is why this mark self-calibrates downward the first time a real compaction is actually witnessed). The exception no longer applies. The hook demands you call AskUserQuestion now, before any other text, and re-fires on every Stop until a real AskUserQuestion appears in the transcript. Only if the tool is genuinely unavailable that turn do you fall back to a caps-locked text warning listing the three options.

What stays your judgment, invisible to the hook: whether the task is closed and the next request is unrelated, whether the remaining work needs the old history, and the focused-work exception itself. The hook computes only the numeric half and hands the decision back to you.

Anti-nag: after a soft fire the hook stays quiet until context grows another ~15% of the window (30k at the 200K default, 150k at 1M; per-session, per-model state in `~/.claude/hooks/state/<session_id>.context.json`). After a hard checkpoint is raised and answered it goes quiet until the same further growth, which near the ceiling usually means auto-compaction handles it. Auto-compaction or `/clear` lowers the count and re-arms the track. Instant off switch: `touch ~/.claude/hooks/context-check.disabled`, back on with `rm`.

Briefly describe the situation in text before asking. The question offers three options:
- **Handoff prompt for a new chat** — generate a self-contained handoff immediately (goal and state, what's done and verified, changed files with paths, decisions made and why, rejected dead ends, exact next steps) entirely inside one standard fenced code block with its copy button, same as CD prompts; the user opens a new chat and pastes it with one click.
- **Clear context, stay here** — you can't do this yourself, just tell them the command to clear the current chat.
- **Keep going** — no change.
